{
  "answer": "**Allama Iqbal's *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*** features a visionary \"Celestial Journey\" (*Sair-e-Falak*) in which the poet, accompanied by Imagination, ascends \"through the cosmic blue,\" passing stars, Paradise (with Tooba's bough and Houris), and descending to a vision of Hell before an angelic revelation.[^1]\n\n**Mpu Dusun's *Kuñjarakarṇa Dharmakathana*** depicts the demon ascetic Kuñjarakarṇa, a sky-traveler, flying to Buddha's monastery, Yama's realm, and explicitly ascending to Indra's heaven—gazing on its eight surrounding abodes (Indra, Agni, Yama, etc.)—as part of his quest for enlightenment.[^2]\n\nNo other works in the corpus describe literal journeys into the heavens; references in Cynewulf's *Andreas* are to souls seeking heavenly joys or angelic travel, but not the protagonist's ascent.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, [Chapter 18: Sair-e-Falak](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/18-sair-e-falak/translation/#p-45fa64).\n\n[^2]: Mpu Dusun, *Kuñjarakarṇa Dharmakathana*, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-kunjarakarna-dharmakathana-894f4a/01/translation/#p-7eadb0).\n\n[^3]: Cynewulf, *Andreas*, [Chapter 1](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-c655bd).",
